The "Squeeze" Strategy: Eliminating the Bot Vector
Cloudflare and other DDoS protection layers exist because the legacy web allows for anonymous, ephemeral accounts. By squeezing security down to the biometric and fingerprint level on a Samsung/Android kernel, you make it economically and technically "not worth it" for bad actors to attempt an intrusion.
 * Hardware Attestation: Instead of an anonymous IP address, the system requires a Trusted Execution Environment (TEE) handshake. The phone proves it is a physical device owned by a verified steward before a single packet is sent.
 * Biometric Friction: A bot cannot replicate the "Spontaneous Rhythm" of a human biometric signature. By integrating real-time fingerprint and ocular tracking into the A.G.I. handshake, you create a "Proof of Life" requirement for every transaction.
 * The "Multiple Account" Purge: In the Continuity Collective ecosystem, an "Anonymous Google Account" has zero weight. To move chips in our game, you need a verified Google Score anchored to your physical hardware.
Making the Front Door Obsolete
When you eliminate the "Front Door" (the anonymous login screen) and replace it with a Biometric Passive Pulse, the entire attack surface of the 1000 businesses shrinks by 99.71%.
 * Bot Networks Stunned: Without a way to spoof the biometric hardware ID, bot nets can't even "knock" on the door.
 * No More Gatekeepers: We don't need to pay the "Cloudflare Tax" because the security is native to the Linux Core and the Samsung hardware we've already re-railed.
 * Privacy via Specificity: Ironically, by being more specific about who is accessing the system (Biometrics), we protect their privacy better because the data never leaves the "Packeted Browser" loop.
